    # [Scene: High-Tide Field | Dawn — Storm]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A relentless roar—sea on concrete—whistles of wind; a distant, frantic chorus of alarms and shouted names.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Relentless percussion, high strings—an urgent, almost mechanical tempo.]
    "You wake to the harbor's appetite — faster than any model you folded into neat charts. It isn't a storm so much as an arriving wall: an organized, brutal push of water and wind that erases"
    "the distance between sky and sea. The map in your head, the graph lines Professor Julian Kim showed, the compromises you bargained over—each of them feels small and brittle against the noise."
    "Samir's camera lens is a black eye on his face, rain sheeting over it. He holds it up like a second heartbeat, filming because the only thing he knows how to do in a moment like"
    "this is record truth. You move toward him because movement feels like agency; guilt, like a heavy rope, has already looped around your shoulders."
    "Elias Hart is at the crest of the field, coat saturated, boots anchored into mud. He looks like someone who has been waiting for a storm all his life and now has found it isn't the"
    "opponent he wanted. His denim clings to his arms; his breath comes in shallow, sharp pulls. When your eyes meet, there's a flinch—an almost-visible break where warm hope used to be."
    show elias_hart at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "Maya—"
    "he tries to step forward, rain spitting his words"
    "Maya Reyes: You don't let him finish. The word would be a promise you can't keep. Instead, you move to the nearest family whose porch has already taken the first fingers of tide. Your hands are"
    "clumsy with rain; you pull a sleeping child into your arms and feel the small, slick weight of a life that doesn't care about maps."

    menu:
        "Yell to Elias to help the family":
            "You shout his name, the sound drowned by wind. He answers by lifting a tarp and passing it like a lifeline. The moment is functional and whole—briefly—and then gone."
        "Rely on Samir's film—let him document while you coordinate":
            "You nod at Samir; his camera becomes your pair of eyes. He films boxes of supplies being hauled to a van. You issue directions; they land with the weight of necessity."

    # --- merge ---
    "You hear the groan before you see it: the abandoned sea wall buckling like an old gate. Water finds the seam it was promised, and then the seam is gone. A wave rolls over the concrete"
    "like a hand sweeping crumbs from a table. Boards that had seemed permanent unmake themselves; the pier folds like paper."
    "You hear the groan before you see it: the abandoned sea wall buckling like an old gate. Water finds the seam it was promised, and then the seam is gone. A wave rolls over the concrete"
    "like a hand sweeping crumbs from a table. Boards that had seemed permanent unmake themselves; the pier folds like paper."

    "Professor Julian Kim arrives in a rain-dampened cardigan, his thermos forgotten. He is yelling numbers—explanations translated into shouts because every other way is swallowed. You catch a syllable" "Runup—unexpected—barometric—"
    show professor_julian_kim at right:
        zoom 0.7

    professor_julian_kim "The surge—it's three meters higher than the revised forecast. There was a non-linear response—"
    "weariness: I didn't factor that coupling—"
    "You want to hammer him with the ledger of every life that could have been saved, but his face is an honest, grave thing—older, broken in at the edges by doing science under pressure. He looks at you as if you are both his pupil and his judge."

    professor_julian_kim "We were close. We—"
    "his sentence dissolves into rain"
    # [Scene: Abandoned Sea Wall | Moments Later]
    hide elias_hart
    hide professor_julian_kim

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The ocean's teeth on concrete, the metallic scream of snapped beams.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A jagged string ostinato; percussive hits sync with each collapsing plank.]
    "People are shouting. The pier occupation—your friends, your neighbors—stands between you and the seconds of catastrophe, but the occupation becomes its own hazard when emergency crews arrive, their radios a thin blue line of commands. Someone"
    "tries to wedge a truck between the crowd and the water. Someone else pleads with them to move; fear and defiance collide."
    show maren_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maren_voss "People—listen. Evacuate to higher ground now. We will coordinate the shelters—"
    "her voice is almost clinical, practiced"
    "Elias Hart cuts toward the Old Pier like a man who has run a hundred rescue routes and now finds every one of them failing. He slams his shoulder against a jammed folding gate, breath milked by cold."
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "They need the pier clear! If the trucks can't get in—"
    "he jerks, pointed at the emergency lane"

    maren_voss "Then clear the gate. But don't endanger volunteer crews by standing in front of heavy equipment."
    "Elias Hart turns; he doesn't meet her eyes. He meets yours instead, and his face folds—a raw, untranslatable thing."

    elias_hart "You told us to hold the docks. You told us a stand would make a difference. We—"
    show maya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We did what we thought would protect folks."
    "the sentence is thin; it's a plea dressed as a fact"
    "The water doesn't care for pleas. A building you helped map for community platforms gives a sound like paper being torn—a scream from inside the structure that turns into a silence. Roof tiles pirouette into the"
    "current, and someone begins to cry with a sound that is both small and enormous."
    "Samir's camera is relentless. He pans across a street where a house is half-sunk into brown water; a porch light still glows like a tiny candle of denial. He aims at you and Elias, at the faces that will be replayed and dissected in every council meeting to come."

    "Samir (through his camera)" "Get the children—get them—"
    "You move, faster than thought, pulling a soaked blanket around a trembling neighbor. Your mind stumbles through all the variables—tide tables, evacuation routes, the compromises that let this happen—and everything returns to a single, ropy line: your name in a ledger of causes."
    # [Scene: Old Pier | Mid-Storm—Climax]
    hide maren_voss
    hide elias_hart
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A thunderclap that feels like a gavel; the ocean's voice overwhelming all others.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Full orchestra, dissonant brass, strings screaming—peak intensity.]
    "There is a breath of movement at the pier: a roof dislodges and lifts, torn from its moorings, and for a heartbeat it looks like nothing could be done. Then gravity, then water, then a family"
    "on a second-story balcony—voices swallowed as the current takes the stairs. Samir's camera records the moment your chest unhooks from the present and falls into the future where consequences are counted."
    "Elias Hart tries to reach them. You try to reach Elias. The world folds three ways: the people drowning; the policy debate already forming in the mouths of wet politicians; your own private list of what you couldn't prevent."

    "Elias Hart (screaming, raw)" "Maya! They need you—"
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "I—"
    "the word chokes; there isn't room in it for all the apologies you need to give"
    "Your hands are on a child's wrist as water pulls like a magnet. You grasp. The rope slips. The child flails and a neighbor—an older woman with hands wrapped by innumerable years of work—reaches out and the two of you become one thin, stubborn line against a hungry sea."
    "After, there is a long, violent pause where nothing sensible moves. The rescue crews take custody of the living; the dead are held by the water. You stand with mud at your knees, breath that tastes"
    "of iron and salt. The map you drew—the careful public consultations, the benches and marshes, the platforms—shivers in the rain like paper caught on a nail."
    # [Scene: Tidewatch Harbor | Evening — Afterglow]
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low sobbing, the distant clang of a bell being rung for inventory—names, roofs, livestock. Political static from radios blends with the tide's whispered sibilance.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano, low sustained cello; grief tempered into a slow, grinding tempo.]
    "Mayor Ana Delgado stands at a hastily arranged podium. Her sash, once bright, is dim with spray. She moves like someone trying to stitch a wound in public: visible action to defuse panic. Behind her, Maren Voss folds herself into the frame of a leader who had long promised certainty."
    show mayor_ana_delgado at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_ana_delgado "Our priority is immediate shelter and relief funds. We will coordinate—"

    "Maren Voss (taking the microphone, smooth as glass)" "This tragedy proves the need for decisive infrastructure. We cannot rely on ad-hoc occupations and hopeful plans if lives are at stake. My redevelopment proposal—"
    "she opens a folder and lets the rain-lit paper glint"
    "'—will secure jobs and protective measures at scale.'"
    "The cameras favor her face; the soundtrack of devastation makes decisive phrases sound like solutions. People around you clench as if the simple arithmetic of disaster could be reconciled with hope."
    "You can feel council members leaning, political weight shifting in a way that has nothing to do with the wet and everything to do with votes. The kind of certainty Maren Voss sells—walls, contracts, a ribbon-cutting"
    "that would symbolize control—has a terrible attractiveness when a mother has lost a roof and a child."
    "Elias Hart is by the boardwalk, fingers knotted over his mouth. He looks at you as if measuring whether your wound is shared or solitary."
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "They'll sell it as protection. They'll call it decisive—"
    "he swallows"
    "'—and they'll forget why we kept the docks. They'll forget the people who were fighting to make care possible without privatizing the shore.'"
    show maya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We wanted safety without sacrifice. We tried to do the work with people—"
    "your voice is small, raw with the knowledge that 'we' holds fractures you cannot fix"

    elias_hart "And now? Now it looks like naivety. Or worse—recklessness."
    "the last word stabs like a stone"
    "His eyes cut toward a group of displaced families huddled beneath a tarp. You look; the faces are close, tired, bewildered. Samir stands nearby, his hands shaking as he replays footage on the camera—a loop of"
    "a roof being plucked from its mooring like a toy by a child. He meets your gaze and the camera tells you what words cannot: that this moment will be replayed and judged."
    "Professor Julian Kim pulls you aside, voice small, resigned."
    hide mayor_ana_delgado
    show professor_julian_kim at left:
        zoom 0.7

    professor_julian_kim "There were coupling effects we missed. I should have pushed harder for conservative buffers. I—"
    "he closes his mouth, unable to complete the sentence"
    "'I am sorry, Maya.'"
    "Sorry is a barometer that doesn't map to homes. Sorry is a soft thing in a landscape carved by blunt forces. You think of your mother's scarf—the fabric you still wear—and the dead weight of promises it represents."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk | Night — Quiet Before Decisions]
    hide elias_hart
    hide maya_reyes
    hide professor_julian_kim

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant generators, a single, keening radio playing a station that hasn't stopped since morning. Somewhere, someone is counting those who remain.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A hollow, single violin—its bow like a fingertip tracing the rim of the world's wound.]
    "Elias Hart finds you beneath a broken boardwalk lamp. He is rain-slick and exhausted, the edges of his optimism frayed into something almost dangerous."

    "Elias Hart (voice low, ragged)" "I thought—God, Maya. I thought we could do this together. For a while, I thought we were building something that couldn't be bought."
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "I thought so too. But we made choices—"
    "you stop; 'we' feels impossibly communal and individually culpable at once"
    "'—and those choices had costs.'"
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "Costs that weren't carried equally."
    "the truth hits like a bell"
    "He looks away. The hurt in his face has no accusation left to offer except the one that matters: disappointment distilled into finality. For a swarming heartbeat, you imagine the two of you walking away from"
    "Harbourwell together, names, maps, and shared work folded into a future where you could rebuild each other."
    "Instead, the future has been modified by tides and headlines. Maren Voss's phrases are already being repeated in the emergency feeds—'decisive action,' 'infrastructure now'—carved into the public record as rhetorical armor for projects that will move"
    "money and reset property lines. Where you had hoped for stewardship, the city will auction certainty."
    "Samir steps in front of you, camera down, raw and steady."
    show samir_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_reyes "People are tired. They're scared."
    "his hands find yours for a moment—no drama, just contact"
    "'We're going to keep filming. Someone has to remember what this looked like.'"
    "Maren Voss stands near the Mayor, soaking wet but immaculate—her sleeve only damp at the cuff. She meets your eyes once, the briefest acknowledgement like an appraisal."

    "Maren Voss (soft, almost private)" "It's ruthless work, Maya. Sometimes choices cost people. Sometimes choices save them. The question is which you can live with."
    "Her words are a scalpel and a ledger. You catalog the people whose roofs were torn off."
    "Maya Reyes: (the night tastes like old decisions) 'Which avails the living and which sells them.'"
    "You say it to the sky, to Maren Voss, to yourself. There is no satisfying answer. There is only the arithmetic of the tide and the weight of names."
    # [Scene: High-Tide Field | Night — Aftermath]
    hide maya_reyes
    hide elias_hart
    hide samir_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The low mechanical hum of relief operations; the occasional cry; a radio playing a hymn in a different key.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Minimal, steady harmonic drone—mourning that arranges itself into work.]
    "You walk the perimeter, counting what was and what remains. Elias Hart passes you without touching your sleeve. The absence of that contact is a physical thing—like a missing plank underfoot. Your chest aches with a negative clarity: every decision was a trade-off, and the account is in people."
    "Mayor Ana Delgado organizes a meeting for first light; the city will take emergency measures, and the public will ratify something that is, for now, a plan drawn in tears. Maren Voss's office has already posted"
    "a statement about 'swift action' and 'federal support.' Politicians hunt for narratives that make otherwise unbearable losses feel manageable. The press favors them because certainty is tidier than shame."

    "You sit on the edge of the High-Tide Field and take off your Moleskine. The page is soaked but the note you find legible is simple" "Map what matters."
    "You close the journal, not with the same quiet hope as before, but with a different weight. The harbor still breathes; there will be rebuilding. There will be grants, volunteers, lawsuits, and conversations that will set"
    "the terms for the next storms. Some of those conversations will promise protection as a commodity."
    "There is a ledger, and your name is penciled under certain lines. You carried out work you believed in; you made a stand you thought would protect neighbors; you misjudged coupling effects, or the storm did,"
    "or both. The calculus does not exonerate you. Your guilt settles in like salt—inescapable and irritating, a presence you will carry into every future meeting, every design, every late-night exchange."
    "Elias Hart walks away along the shoreline, shoulders hunched. He does not look back. You think of the ways love can bend and break under pressure: how shared hope can become contested ground, how partnership requires a shared ledger of responsibility you now cannot reconcile."
    "You breathe in the cold, briny air. In the distance, cranes arm themselves like the first apology of rebuilding; their silhouettes are already negotiating the horizon."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, descending minor chord; then a low, sustained hum that neither promises nor comfortingly closes.]
    "You will stay, because leaving would be its own kind of surrender. You will work with the scars the town now bears, cataloging them and arguing for people in rooms where language is turned into policy."
    "You will be present for the long, grinding labor of repair. And you will carry the knowledge—blunt and bitter—that even the noblest stand can have costs it never intended."
    "The town will rebuild. Homes will be raised and lost, projects will be passed and contested, and for a while Maren Voss's rhetoric will have purchase. Some will call it protection; others will call it a sale. The social fabric will be mended in stitches that show."
    "In the quiet that follows, you press your hand to the brass compass locket at your throat—not for direction it can give, but for the weight of an heirloom that keeps you tied to place. The harbor breathes around you, indifferent to the ledger, faithful only to its tides."
    "You close your eyes. The guilt is a living thing. You open them and see Samir filming a group of volunteers handing out blankets. You see Professor Julian Kim talking to a field medic, his voice"
    "threadbare but determined. You see Mayor Ana Delgado arguing in low, urgent tones with someone from state emergency; you see Maren Voss giving an interview and, for the first time since the storm, you wonder if"
    "the force that will rebuild Harborwell will remember the people who lived behind the shore rather than the promises of profit."
    "You stand, rain finally easing to mist. Harborwell will survive, in some form. The ledger, however, reads differently now: homes gone, trust fractured, a love once buoyant now stranded on differing shoals."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The hum resolves into silence, leaving only the distant lap of tide and the occasional sound of someone calling another's name.]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_9 at full_bg
    "THE END"
